  "version": "1.0",
  "schemaSlice": "courtCategoryMappings",
  "provider": "JTI",
  "loggedStep": "Step #54 — KD-001 Option B closure; Step #57 — 4 new Madera mappings (411100→CIV, 213110→FAM, 606110+612110→MEN) via direct CMS list-query; Step #58 — added per-code codelistLabels (180 entries from scripts/madera_case_category.txt) for human-readable rendering in SearchCase UI; Step #59 — exhaustive unmapped-code probe (probe-step59-unmapped.ps1) promoted 63 evidence-backed codes (42→105: +41 CIV, +1 CIV/SmallClaims 711110, +17 FAM, +3 PRB, +1 MEN) with PERFECT filter fidelity (0/85 evidence codes returned any caseCategoryCode other than the one queried). 19 searchable CRI codes + 3 self-typed ADMIN codes (110120 Lodged Will, 110210 Sanctions, 120110 Juror OSC) deliberately NOT mapped — searchability proven but workflow/policy NOT validated; documented in JtiCaseCategoryPolicy.json step59 audit block + CRI policy evidence.",
  "description": "Per-court CASE_CATEGORY codelist projections onto JCCC 3-letter policy entries. Closes KD-001 (Flat CASE_CATEGORY codelist namespace) by introducing explicit court-id scoping. Each top-level `courts.<courtId>.categoryCodeToJccc` map projects that court's numeric (or alpha) per-court CASE_CATEGORY codelist values to the canonical JCCC 3-letter policies declared in JtiCaseCategoryPolicy.json. The resolver `JtiFieldSchemaProvider.FindPolicyByCourtCategoryCode(courtId, code)` is the sole consumer.",
  "policyFileRef": "JtiCaseCategoryPolicy.json",
  "designRationale": "Per the JTI vendor doc quote in JtiCaseCategoryPolicy.json: 'The Journal Technologies case management system (CMS) allows each California Court to configure their system to precisely meet their requirements... You must assume that EACH Court will have different Court Policy values from each other.' Different courts may use different codelist conventions (LASC alpha codes 'LC'/'UD' vs Placer numeric '421110'). The flat pre-Step-#54 resolver `FindPolicyByCourtCategoryCode(code)` silently assumed a single global namespace, which would break on any second-court onboarding. This mapping file makes the per-court projection explicit and KD-001 architecturally closed.",
  "addingNewCourtChecklist": [
    "1. Add a new top-level entry under `courts.<courtId>` with the court's identifier (lowercase, matches `CourtConfiguration.CourtId`).",
    "2. Populate `categoryCodeToJccc` with each court-specific code → JCCC mapping. Codes are case-insensitive strings; JCCC values must reference an existing policy key in JtiCaseCategoryPolicy.json (e.g., 'CIV', 'UD', 'FAM', 'PRB', 'MEN', 'JUV', 'CRI', 'APP').",
    "3. Codes may be NUMERIC (Placer/Madera shape — '407200') OR ALPHA (LASC shape — 'UD', 'LC') per the per-court convention.",
    "4. The same numeric code MAY appear in multiple courts mapped to DIFFERENT JCCCs — that's the whole point of court-scoping. (Pre-Step-#54 this would have silently misclassified; post-#54 the resolver is courtId-aware.)",
    "5. Run the full test suite — Step54_KD001ClosureTests will verify the new court entry's shape integrity."
  ],
